CRIMEAN-CONGO HEMORRHAGIC FEVER - PAKISTAN (17): (BALOCHISTAN)
**************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this posting:
[1] EpiCore Surveillance Project response
[2] Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa

******
[1] EpiCore Surveillance Project response
Date: Sat 7 Oct 2017
From: Muhammad Hakim Khan [edited]


[re: ProMED-mail Crimean-Congo hem. fever - Pakistan (16): (BA) RFI 20171008.5365206]
----------------------------------------------------------------------
CCHF surveillance is ongoing in Balochistan and a fellow of FELTP [Field Epidemiology and Laboratory Training. Program] is assigned by DGHS [Directorate General Health Services] Balochistan for updates. During the last week one suspected case was reported. The case was a 58-year-old woman from district Qilla Abdullah, with history of high-grade fever, body aches, bleeding from nose and mouth, and animal contact history. She was admitted in the isolation ward, her PCR was positive for CCHF. The patient expired while under treatment. Now a total of 69 CCHF cases with 11 deaths have been reported till [Sun 1 Oct 2017], of which a total of 23 were confirmed by lab.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Surveillance Project member
Muhammad Hakim Khan
FELTP Pakistan

ProMED thanks Muhammad Hakim Khan for the comments to our posting on CCHF cases in Balochistan as well as the epidemiological information. - Mod.UBA

******
[2] Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa
Date: Sun 8 Oct 2017
From: Muhammad Hakim Khan [edited]


CCHF case from Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa
---------------------------------
During the last week [week of Sun 1 Oct 2017] one suspected CCHF case was reported from Hayat Abad Medical Complex (HMC), Peshawar. The patient is a 40-year-old male from Sikander Khel bala, district Bannu, with onset of symptoms from [14 Sep 2017] and admitted at HMC on [29 Sep 2017] with fever, body aches, vomiting, and bleeding tendency (nose and gums). His initial platelet count was 65 000 at the time of admission. He had a history of animal contacts at home. His blood sample was collected for CCHF serology, which was reported positive for CCHF. All of his contacts including the health care providers have been noted. One of the close contacts has developed fever and he has been hospitalized and is being investigated while the remaining contacts are stated to be stable at the moment and they will be followed for 14 days.

--
Communicated by:
EpiCore Surveillance Project member
Muhammad Hakim Khan
FELTP Pakistan

[ProMED thanks Muhammad Hakim Khan for the information regarding another CCHF case in Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa, which has not been reported previously by ProMED-mail. - Mod.UBA

